This show was part of the Summer Camp Music Festival. During the rain delay, the band played a second acoustic set in the crowd. Kurt & Pete were on unplugged guitars, Trev on his unplugged bass, Ben on djembe, and JonL on cowbell. After music was stopped during the first set, the weather was so bad for so long that Goose would not have gotten to get back on stage if it wasn't for lespecial, Brass Against, and the Summer Camp Staff at the Soulshine tent for coming up with a new schedule, which cut time from their sets, but allowed all three bands to play music. Huge thanks to everyone involved!! 
Set 1: 11:02pm - 11:10pm
Set 2: (no time recorded, things were hectic) 
Set 3: (Resumes playing on stage) 1:20am - 1:57am

jamchart_notes: Monster AIN w/ multiple amazing movements. Pete opens things with incredible synth work, but Spuds is the real star; driving this monster jam towards a magnificent melodic peak! Some very funky playing from Richk closes this all-timer.

The Buffalo Arcadia: An iconic fan favourite. Rick's bright rhythm playing spurs Peter into an uplifting bliss segment early on, which leads to several minutes of sustained soloing. Seemingly ends and then gets revived by the band for another extended run around pure euphoria before returning home. Recommended for a sunny afternoon.

jamchart_notes: A twisting “fast Need” with a danceable exploratory initial jam that pivots over a drum break into a more dynamic guitar-led section. As Rick passes the baton to Trevor, they descend into an almost marching section with a syncopated drum line and thumping bassline. Rick finds a new melody that the band quickly backs as a looping hook that naturally summons the composed tail.

jamchart_notes: Efficient Pete-led 14-minute journey initiated by his vibesy accompaniment as Rick arpeggiates out of the head section. A soaring synth jam that starts bright and clean morphs into a grittier sawtoothy lead section before landing them into a floating full-band jam with sort of “Scarlet”-islandy motif undergirded by rolling drum fills and well-placed Trevor flair. Rick leads out from there with a punchy attack that twists the tropical theme into a short but assertive closing statement.

This show was the first night of the Bingo Tour. The whole setlist was chosen based on random draws of bingo balls with different songs or gimmicks on them. This was Jeff's first show with the band.

jamchart_notes: One of the finest versions ever played. Incredible and soaring Rick.
shownotes: This show was the first night of the Bingo Tour. The whole setlist was chosen based on random draws of bingo balls with different songs or gimmicks on them. This was Jeff's first show with the band.

footnote: Included "Take A Lap" and "Coach on Rainstick" bingo balls. Each band member and Coach took a lap around the barn.
jamchart_notes: A first jam that stays within bounds but explodes with the power of the sun leads into a second jam where the band members each have to "Take a Lap". Peter steps out early with aggressive guitar riffing as Rick and the drums lock in on each other as the music takes on a runaway freight train vibe. When Spuds finally takes his turn, Jeff picks up the beat out of the fragmented space and crafts an airy, major-key jam. Coach hops on rainstick and Rick adds some vocalizing as it slowly and patiently winds down.
shownotes: This show was the first night of the Bingo Tour. The whole setlist was chosen based on random draws of bingo balls with different songs or gimmicks on them. This was Jeff's first show with the band.

footnote: FTP. Mystery Song #1. Included "15 Minute Jam" bingo ball.
jamchart_notes: Mystery Ball #1 for Bingo Tour N1 resulted in what might be considered one of their most epic FTP jams ever due to +15 minute jam bingo ball pulled as song ended. Funky groovy start that turns melodic and once Ben picks up the pace, Rick rips one of his patented, god-like shred peaks.

jamchart_notes: Two main segments to this monster. Rick initially crafts a soaring hose motif as he and Peter really lock in on the dual guitars. As the first peak fades away, we are treated to a flamethrower of a ripping jam, going around for more and more builds before finally screaming into the finish. Winner of JOTY 2020.
The legendary HOSEWOOD. Must-hear.
Tender and gorgeous play. Really beautiful stuff.
Encore/Final Song of an incredible show, this is one of the happiest, most melodic, pleasing jams you will hear before a fiery, passionate finish.

jamchart_notes: Grippo adds beautifully to the Type I section of the jam. Out of the space, Spuds kicks into a funk groove and the band dives headfirst into a space highly reminiscent of Herbie Hancock. Rick and Grippo trade licks off each other like old friends while Peter saws away at grimy rhythm guitar. Builds in this zone for a while and is a must-hear piece of improv.

jamchart_notes: Inspiring, get-your-ass-out-bed-and-do-something-with-your-life first jam, followed by groove dance party and epic re-build to glory.

Eschews the first jam and goes right into the driving second after the "whoa" section. Immedate and FURIOUS dual-guitar attack. Peter goes ham on envelope filter early on before Rick takes control and shreds.

Typical groove fest that settles down before incredible interplay between Rick and Peter. Driving bass and pulsating drumming and percussion pick jam back up. Peter then starts sirens and comes in hot before letting Ben close out with some very cool soloing.

First version with the drum break after the first chorus. The band takes the jam with ferocity, building in a linear fashion yet engaging in amazing interplay on the way to several peaks. Crashes back into the ending and Spuds plays us into the opening of "Drive" in lieu of a second jam.

jamchart_notes: 30-minute version stays relatively close to home until around 19 minutes, when it shifts to a bright and major key. This vibe gradually picks up steam before peaking again and transitioning > to "Caution".
First jammed version in a while goes for it and reaches an awesome major-key peak before slamming -> to the ending of "Time to Flee".
Fall '21 was a great time for "Dragonfly" - emerges perfectly out of "Spirit of the Dark Horse" to close the set.
First version with the full Peter organ solo. Soars to the heavens.
The first "With" and perhaps the best, the contemplative jam gains in energy before exploding into the final chorus of "All I Need".
Standard jam fades into a GORGEOUS motif. You may not realize it initially, but it becomes clear that the segue -> to "Crosseyed and Painless" is imminent.
All-around balls-to-the-walls energy. Rick absolutely torches Kansas City while Spuds spurs him on. Expressive vocal ending.

jamchart_notes: Shorter version but brimming with passion throughout. Gorgeous cool down mid-jam that rises patiently and blissfully. True glory hose finish before returning to song ending.
Swirling, chaotic, yet in control. Slight cool down before swirl picks back up amid organ-driven finish.
Melodic jamming slowly swelling particularly as Pete ramps up on second guitar. Seemingly coming to a grand finish, they take a lovely quieter approach for the final four minutes.
Much like the Terminal 5 "Look Out Cleveland", the Mission "Rockdale" just builds into this intense "Arcadia"-like jam and peaks spectacularly.
Vibey "Tumble" gets a jam for the first time, gradually picking up speed until a high-speed peak closes it out.

Show opener for a fan favorite show, jam starts in earnest at the 10:30 mark and stays within a pretty standard rocking tempo throughout. Ripping final peak and cool final minute cooldown into "Travelers."

The Mission Arcadia: After funky start, band collectively builds into one of Goose’s most blissful & beautiful jams ever. After return to song ending (watch video for “THE LOOK”), Denver is obliterated by one of their most majestic peaks in history.

jamchart_notes: Fitting encore for the final show in an incredible Fall ‘21 tour. Riffing around the FF song at start of jam, then dark "Crazy Train" CCP style jamming before bringing the tour home in an enthusiastic fashion.

Soak in this Flee as a peaceful gentleness settles in to start. Gorgeous keys by Peter and Rick mimics the style. Like a flowing wave, Trevor and percussion begin increasing tempo and volume as band rises magically only to settle back down in the earlier quiet style, then build back to a fiery finish.
Second-ever "Bob Don With". Really nice contemplative jam.
Melodious and smooth, driven by Peter's grooves.

Show opener for NYE ‘21, starting as a type 1 rocker with melodic playing by Rick and Trevor and Peter laying some lovely supporting guitar effects. Cooldown ensues until drumming intensifies and band power towards the finish.

jamchart_notes: Melts into nothingness before before building back into seemingly everything in a spectacular white-knuckle peak then gorgeously -> "Rosewood Heart".
This first jam peaks so insanely hard, Rick is in full god mode. Excellent second jam akin to "speed jazz" circa Summer '93 Phish and -> "Echo of a Rose" ending.
Trevor leads the band into a jam that's almost like Phish's "Wolfman's Brother".

July 1999. Jetta Factory. Guangzhou, CN. In a syncopated rhythmic dance the Furbys whir & clink down the assembly line. A sudden burst of deafening light incinerates workers as the Phoenix apparates, providing a new directive. Tiger Electronics source code overwritten w/ dark sentience. Beaks accented w/ razor blades. Eyes w/ lasers. Fur w/ mecha scales. Wings snap into place. With cries of mangled Furbish, the nightmare creatures swarm like bats through the window above to carry out their terrible mission.
Melodic major key goodness through. Similar feel and vibes as the Mission Arcadia (perhaps highlighted by Peter’s keys), with uplifting beautiful finish.
The younger sibling of 1/30 and 3/1. Hits on dark themes but doesn't explore them to the same extent as the other two Winter 2022 behemoth "Wysteria".
Gold standard for blissful early jamming section with Pete's gorgeous keys and an all-time Rick solo. Standard but dance-filled groove in second half.

jamchart_notes: 38 minute two part monster. First 23 minutes highlight Goose’s ability to drive their jams in different directions. Second begins with a clear shift into Echo, resulting in an Echo jam and finishing into an epic raging peak.
Gets a second outro jam for the first time ever. Gorgeous major-key playing.
Peter plays with the reverb on the organ early on in the jam for a haunting vibe.

jamchart_notes: Relentless and long first jam seamlessly transitions between major and minor key. Short second jam sees Peter doing some sparse organ leading before landing in "California Magic".
Ultra-funky molasses jamming. Trevor puts on a clinic concocting murderous bass lines while Rick lets his inner SRV come out to play, absolutely scorching blues soloing.

Typically beautiful "Sea" jam fragments into intense, evil noises, making you grab your blanket for dear life as Peter cackles among looping marimba arpeggiators, Rick effects, and other general madness. Would be right at home as a "Dr. D" intro but resolves instead into a fantastic "Factory Fiction" set closer.
Classic > from "Jive I." Jam immediately takes a darker turn behind Peter’s Nord synth and settles into a vibey groove. Unique version.

On this Bird's lucky voyage #7 we become hypnotized by cyclical dizzying flight patterns while a menacing undercurrent of fuzzed out Fuck Buttons-esque synth washes and coordinated sonic booms slowly cracks open a glowing fissure in the Earth, the triumphant cries of the Ashebird grow ever murderous and it goes in for the kill, ripping our face clean off our head and sending us plummeting to our molten doom.

The name of the game is efficiency. Trevor plows forward into the minor key out of his solo and the drummers develop a deep pocket. Peter hits the clav and Rick hangs back for a while to let him rip before taking the reins himself. Goes straight for the jugular and doesn't let up for a second.

jamchart_notes: This truly elite “All I Need” is dark Goose jamming at its finest. Trevor-forward full band interplay with Spuds mimicking a violent half-speed thrash metal death march creates space for Rick to swirl brain-breaking minor-key runs over a bed of extra-terrestrial synths. If aliens ever attack, they’ll come blaring a six-minute loop of this jam on repeat from their flying saucer Alpines. The accidental second jam features some fine clav-work from Peter and an extended moody intro to “Nights in White Satin”.

jamchart_notes: Multi-section masterpiece taking a journey through time & space. After breakdown/opening jam, band builds up to evil psychotic heavy metal shredding. Pete then switches to keys, Jeff adds chimes & Rick performs one of his most beautiful solos ever. Winner of JOTY 2022.

The song's 2022 evolution really begins here as the band opts to jam out of Rick's solo section. Great keys work from Peter eventually morphs into a layered motif with excellent use of space by Peter on organ while Rick unleashes some dark-ish soloing. Under-the-radar yet excellent jam.

jamchart_notes: Peter expertly controls the mood on this festival highlight encore, moving the jam sections along from clav, to vibraphone/piano, to an unconventional and experimental arpeggiator transition into the ending breakdown.

Strong dual guitar attacking jam changes dramatically and beautifully as Pete shifts to synth effects around 18:45, creating a space groove and allowing Trevor and Ben to shine. Pete goes to keys a few minutes later as band builds up to a rocking finish.
Went Gin-like Magic. One of the happiest jams you’ll hear emerges in the last 6 minutes. Rick finds a gorgeous hook and band builds until they find collective joyful hose.

jamchart_notes: Double guitar rock with energetic, ripping initial 11 minutes. Jam then begins to get weird and devolve into dark space. Manic alien-style effects develop and haunting synths surround a slow, patient march to the finish.

footnote: Slow, melodic version. With Sinnerman teases.
jamchart_notes: 36 min monster throws down. Very short first jam (ends at 9:15) leads to their longest second jam ever. Very patient jams with short melodic sections intertwined with spacey synths. Jam never quite reaches heights of other AINs but quite the journey.

Hauntingly beautiful jam finds potential trouble as Rick breaks a string (16:45ish). Instead Peter synths & Trevor bass fill the void powerfully allowing Rick to rejoin (18:30) transforming the jam into a slow, evil abduction of the Chrysalis crowd.
Last 5 minutes are spectacular, arena-ready rocking. They catch a lightning in a bottle theme here and jam the hell out of it to a ripping, frenzied peak.

Gorgeous early jam followed by groovy dance-funk. Right before 13 mins, band slows groove & locks in patiently. Tumble tease @ 17:40 creates driving jam leading to collective repeating theme. Band eggs on crowd Woos & melts jam away.

Absolute perfect 2-guitar goose with both guitarists feeling it and toggling seamlessly between dark, penetrating  and celebratory, frolicking jams and back again! It was a special jam where the crowd could sense greatness the moment they veered away from the song!

jamchart_notes: Peter begins the jam with searing synth textures from his Nord Lead before switching to Vibe as a more melodic theme takes shape. The band fully explores this before bringing it home with a typically raging ending.

footnote: With Trey Anastasio on guitar and vocals.
jamchart_notes: Donning cap, goggles, & scarf you rev your doghouse engine and take to the sky, faithful yellow co-pilot at your side. Engaging The Big Red Baron you move into a graceful aerial dance, as many shots dodged as fired. With the Baron finally in your cross-hairs, a lurch & deafening BANG before you pull the trigger. Drat! What’s this? Woodstock is flying toward the Baron, looking orange and shifting redder. Sabotage! Betrayal! Your foes heckle you as your ruined engine sputters and you glide downward, defeated.

jamchart_notes: This Old Trey sings backups & takes a solo during the song before immersing into another multi-section Taboose 2022 jam. Gorgeous bliss>rocking peaks>diving into the weird unknown in another great example of how locked in they all were this tour.

jamchart_notes: The "Madhuvanastasio." Peter initiates a descending "Mind Left Body"-like progression on marimba piano as Rick and Trey dance around each other's melodies. songname: Can't Get You Out Of My Head

jamchart_notes: The rhythm section keeps the pace up while Peter lays down a bright progression. The band jams on a theme akin to "Love is a Battlefield" before transitioning neatly to "Electric Avenue."
Atypical arpeggiator starts off the first headlining performance of 2023. The band vibes and gets loose within the confines of the groove before finishing "Electric Avenue" from Okeechobee.

footnote: Eddy Grant. Ending only, finishing the version from 3/3/23 Okeechobee.

jamchart_notes: Right out of the gate, the band dives into some Winter '22-style dark jamming. Peter goes to a haunting upright piano tone as he and Rick lock in. Spuds shoots the improv into a swirling vortex that transitions cleanly into some bluesy rock at Rick's urging. Organ and guitar trade riffs before Rick steers the band into three-chord bliss. Trevor really steps out on the sustained full-band peak w/ envelope filter work as the joyous peak wraps back to "AIN" proper and a second jam fakeout into "Dr. D."

footnote: With Earthling or Alien? tease from Trevor.
jamchart_notes: Extra-mustard version with a Trevor Bass solo.

footnote: With Jive II teases from Trevor.
jamchart_notes: Boundary-pushing jam highlighted by Rick's dreamlike trills at 12:45 and Peter's synths at 14:58. Hazy ambient drift with no end goal, and no need for one - just totally locked in and thematic jamming: brilliant sign for the Cap & Spring Tour.

Fiery Type 1 jam breaks at 12:16 into open plane of space highlighted by Trevor Bass. A contemplative & melancholic jam emerges, bringing to mind Talk Talk and The Cure, centered around gorgeous leads from Rick & Peter before > to "Doobie."

All-time first jam that starts off with fiery Rick shredding and melts into one of the most beautiful sections of patient, double-guitar bliss you will hear. Second jam contains a funk party that ends with Loose Ends jamming.
Dark, eerie jamming (almost but not quite Crazy Train) that begins to speed up relentlessly, quiets down before the close and then returns to Rockdale out of a tension-filled frenzy.

footnote: With Pick Up The Pieces teases from Rick and Peter.
jamchart_notes: Double guitar funk, effect-filled start that takes a melodic turn as Pete switches to keys. Very cool ending as Rick finds a repeating theme he toys around as the rest of the band builds around him.
Percussive and taut jamming around the Rosewood theme leads to a hypnotic jamming segment on the backhalf when the rythm section hooks up with Rick & Peter channeling Neu! & Kraftwerk.
Haunting yet patient dark opening jam takes off in the 13th minute and never lets up again. Melodic happiness ensues (with Loose Ends teases) and continues to build into peak after glorious peak.

jamchart_notes: The sun beats down as the galleon plods rhythmically through the gentle open ocean. An alarm cry from the crows nest. The quiet sea begins to boil as the terrible mecha phoenix of the Enemy rises from the water and into the sky. Cries of terror and resignation as the creature bursts aflame and slams its wings into the hull in a furious rage, capsizing and igniting the vessel as the horribly blackened crew all sink lifelessly to their demise.

footnote: Fast version. With Camino teases from Peter.
jamchart_notes: Longest jam to date. Multi-sectional behemoth. Cathartic bliss begins as band shakes off PA issues. "Loose Ends" hints lead into a deep funk "Camino" jam as TREVOR BASS makes the filth even filthier. From there, Rick leads into a segment similar to "SOS" or the "Crosseyed and Painless" intro jam as Peter warms up on Vibe. A final pivot into a long, evil build similar to the Philly "Echo" with some foot-guitar action from Peter explodes back into the song. Fully engaging throughout.

jamchart_notes: A serious triumph for fans of patient and psychedelic Goose. Everyone hangs back and just chills in the space as Rick influences with heavy delay and echo loops. Peter soaks it all up with thick Vintage Vibe works as the rhythm section holds it all down. Increases in intensity yet remains calm through a haze of synthesizer and Goedde's light curtain. Unreal.

Getting 2nd set opener treatment, jam turns darker and more exploratory than we’ve seen from "Empress" to date after typical rocking start. After soaking in this space, Ben goes double time and Pete turns on lasers for shredding alien abduction.
Gentle, delicate start that patiently builds to wonderful soaring peak before beautifully melting away into "Peggy-O."
Clav-driven funk to start and finishing with fire, this version is a raging, emphatic ending to an unbelievable stretch of music that began with "Borne."

jamchart_notes: Another notch in the belt of the early '23 "Borne" dominance. The must-hear jam starts out minimalistic and hypnotic, similar to the Eugene version. Peter pushes the band out of the murkiness and into some dark jamming which leads to a hair-raising and triumphant peak.

A jam that Peter would write home about, two guitar Goose locks in immediately. Peter finds a nasty repeating hook at 14:20 that band centers and builds around. In 19th minute, band cools jam down and a few minutes later Peter begins soloing melodically and beautifully on the keys. Goose slowly and magically builds around Pete once again and finishes in gorgeous fashion.

jamchart_notes: Second big Boston "E or A?" of 2023. Jam begins to break into space with some octave-up from rick and reverb-drenched marimba from Peter, though still anchored in the song's progression. Second half hits double-time and explodes outward into a sunny afternoon of a peak. Just nonstop momentum.

Dark and synthy. Learning lessons from each version on the road to Boston, this one has some amazing eerie texturing from Peter, while Rick and Trevor growl in the darkness. Gradually picks up steam with the same ominous Prophet synth undertone throughout. Excellent display of tension-building here.

An important stop on the journey to the insanity at Red Rocks in just a few weeks, we are treated to another dive into Vintage Vibe darkness as the rhythm section holds down a beautiful bedrock for Rick and Peter to weave around each other. Run through a brick wall with the momentum of this one.

jamchart_notes: Whether you think it's the JOTY or not, this "Thatch" is a seriously dense listen. Dark and percussive at first, it feels very typical for the tour but quickly heads into evil territory thanks to Rick and Peter's interplay. Spuds pivots into a charging beat at the 18th minute and they just go for it. Superlatives can't even do this peak justice - needs to be listened. Rick plays with his Whammy at the apex before they execute a perfect and towering return to the song proper. All-timer.

jamchart_notes: Standard fare until the last five minutes or so, when the band breaks into some terrifyingly evil improv. Layers of dark textures thanks to Peter's synths and clav while Rick opts for some more laid-back riffing. One of the best segments of the tour.

songname: Can't Get You Out Of My Head
jamchart_notes: The third festival "Kylie" of the year breaks from form in an amazing "Elmeg the Wise"-like jam. Triumph.
Eschews the usual blistering and fast-paced jam in favour of a laid-back and major-key space. Shorter version that will draw you in for repeated listens.

Peppy jam begins with Spuds on punchy tom work as Peter lays into the Vibe. Turns spacey and then falls away into a bouncy funk jam that feels totally unique to Goose's sound. Trevor and Rick lock in on some riffs while Peter moves to a textural role throughout the contemplative and unhurried groove. Must-listen to understand the developmental period of Fall '23.

jamchart_notes: Newly rearranged "EMG" jam segment is perfectly suited to the pure evil that develops at Red Rocks. Locking in on a theme like the hallowed 1/30/22 "Wysteria" and 6/10/22 "AIN," Rick just doesn't let up for a second as Spuds and Jebb go wild on the primal drums. Trevor drops massive bombs as Peter hammers piano chords and the darkness just BUILDS. Absolutely astounding improv.
Closes the first set like its recent counterpart in Oakland. Gets outside of standard "Yeti" for some fun peak jamming.
Continuation of the mellower and more upbeat "Thatch" style seen at the Wiltern on 9/28. Rocking first half transitions into a quieter space that builds into an excellent peak.

This top shelf "Factory Fiction" jam begins with a snarling slow burn. Eventually finding its way into a patiently developed anthemic Rick-led "Dragonfly" jam, this sonic assault on the alien landscape of Red Rocks concludes in an explosive fashion that merits repeat listens.

jamchart_notes: Moving with peak efficiency this "Red Bird" drops into darkness more quickly than a Spirit Halloween can fill the void of a dead retail store. The summoned Avian Entity arrives and decides to have a bit of fun on this day. Playfully tugged at like psychic marionettes, the members of Goose channel an impromptu film score to the River Spirit’s arrival at the Aburaya Bathhouse, tapping “Moby” to complete the scene.

jamchart_notes: Free-flowing, collective no-one-take-the-lead improv as you can find little moments throughout where any 2 band members riff of each other only to have the others join in. Gradual, patient build leading to explosive peak.

Quickly heads for Winter 2022-style dark jamming. Trevor gets DEEP into Spuds' pocket as Rick's angular soloing swirls around Peter's eerie piano. Synths come in as it gets heavier and into some carnival-like zones before the band bails back into the "Echo" ending.

jamchart_notes: Immediately dropping into a darker key akin to the Red Rocks version, this jam pulsates and is driven forward by ferocious drumming, slowly building to majestic glorious rock.

jamchart_notes: After funky start where Luigi finds his coins, Peter layers mystical synths and Rick finds a haunting repeating riff that propels a wonderfully unique and enchanting version. Thrilling finish.

Blistering Type I play cools into a brief "Shama" fakeout before Goose unleashes one of the best bliss jams in recent memory. Calling to mind the Cap "Drive," each member takes their time with the theme and delivers an absolutely incredible peak.

After Peter tells crowd they have one more song, Rick rips back into a second Drive jam to end the show. A fiery theme develops and eventually morphs into the "(dawn)" finish. Incredible spontaneous moment.

jamchart_notes: “DDS”/“The Doctor Will See You Now” vocal shenanigans lead to gorgeous bliss. Ben eventually hits double time and jam builds to soaring, beautiful first climax. In 16th minute, they return to traditional "Madhuvan" rocking. Peter takes lead with a few playful piano solos before Rick storms back in for an another blistering peak. Just when you think it may be winding down in minute 21, band rips back in and explodes the finish. One of the best jams, if not the best, of Euro Tour 23.

jamchart_notes: The band spends the first minutes after the vocal rounds poking at the edges of the melody until finally casting the bit. Then it's drill, baby, drill. The jam loops, but with purpose. It takes a pointed journey, uncovering new layers as it spirals deeper into the core of its oblique melody, creating an ever-changing tapestry of sound. Cotter energetically closes his first "Bird" with rolling tom work over creative breakbeats while Rich toys with an almost Middle Eastern "Minarets"-style riff.

jamchart_notes: Jam begins from nothing as Rick begins to build a sinister motif. Peter lays down delayed Vibe as the rest of the band enters and gradually build into a beautifully evil churn. Rick then signals to Cotter at the apex and the drums drive forward into double-time, bringing us home in a blaze of glory to bookend this second set. Some really wild and articulate heavy metal builds from Rick.

jamchart_notes: First jammed version since 10/6/22 gets into an airy space quickly with Rick sticking to form at first.

Peter goes full Cory Wong mode on the initial jam segment as he takes a stroll around the stage. Eschewing the typical B-flat modulation to go into jam territory, the band fragments out of the funk and quickly builds into gorgeous major-key play led by Vintage Vibe and Rick's emotional soloing. Cotter picks up the tempo post-peak and Rick lets Peter take the lead as they blaze into the finish of an excellent jam and set.

jamchart_notes: The fabled 31-minute "Cape Cod" of Vampire Weekend dreams. Cotter and CT really lock in here as the band gets into uncharted territory. Hits some Allman Brothers bliss (much to the excitement of Rick and Ezra), then some great clav funk ahead of the song's conclusion. "Those guys can hang!"
A good omen for 2024, "Arrow" makes good use of its time in the first outing of the year. The band drops into a late-night OB-6 space for a while before an explosive conclusion.

footnote: With Welcome to Delta and Dripfield teases from Peter.
jamchart_notes: Goes absolutely balls-to-the-walls for the first jam, getting to high speeds and intensity while Rick absolutely unleashes on the eager crowd. Back half is a nice and patient dual-guitar space that segues nicely into "Dripfield" to complete the Driptych.

jamchart_notes: A sludgy and mysterious exit from the song structure leads to some typical jamming that progressively gets more melodic over the course of 12 minutes or so until Rick latches onto the theme that becomes the centerpiece. He deftly builds up to the peak backed by Cotter’s staccato attack for 5 minutes of triumphant glory. We don’t know what we’ve won, but we’re certain we’re victorious.

jamchart_notes: Cotter's first "AIN" opens summer tour on a strong note. Gets into some percussive space before a brief major section gives way to a spacier and dark-tinged mode. Peter goes to guitar for the last few minutes as they explore some new territory before sliding perfectly -> to "Flee."

Initial standard "Borne" jamming gets into some weird territory just before the 20-minute mark thanks to Cotter and Trevor. Envelope filter bass gets augmented by choppy clav from Peter as Rick lays down loops, eventually smoothly morphing into an upbeat and rocking peak. Hell of an omen for the rest of tour.

Rick's new synth pedal gets a workout as the band plays the first of many amazing versions of "Empress" in summer '24. Late-night disco groove emerges, which will be a prevalent theme throughout the tour.

The band departs from initial funk together in a rocking progression with Peter laying down chunky guitar behind Rick's soloing. Downshifts with a major modulation and follows a familiar uplifting pattern as Cotter pushes the tempo. Hits a strong peak before returning to funk and hints at "Arrow" ahead of the song's conclusion.

Circular patterns of tension and darkness develop as Cotter's fluidity shines. Builds layers and layers of unease as Peter hits sirens and Rick gets dissonant. Amazing stuff that can be likened to a mid-90s "Stash."

Roaring down the open road, radio blaring “...and the road goes on forever I’ve got one more silver...”, feeling mellow mischievous, the sea pans into view. Now barreling along the cliffs the Rider abruptly plunges into the sea, radio cut dead in the depths replaced by embryonic deep whooshing saline heartbeat. Feeling a needful pull toward the surface a triumphant new driving rhythm crackles the airwaves while screaming ablaze toward shouts emanating from vermin in their wooden coffin soon-to-be a pyre.

footnote: The Beatles. With Welcome to Delta teases from Peter.
jamchart_notes: Blasts out of an excellent "Red Bird" into a blistering hot jam.

All-out disco dance party. First "Lee" to ever hit 20 minutes stays in a steady pocket with digital sauce from Rick and OB-6 work from Peter. Trevor steps in with a new progression that deepens the vibe as Cotter stays heavy on toms. Eventually increases in intensity and rages into the finish. Stellar version.

jamchart_notes: A gorgeous two-guitar bliss jam that unfurls into the mountain air. A mood of exuberance throughout.

The band sits in Type I "Hungersite" territory for most of the jam, giving the impression of a conscious effort to resist full peak mode for as long as possible. By the time they get there, there's some undertones of heavy rock and Cotter leads into a half-time shred mode for the final minute that's absolutely amazing.
Quickly departs "Drip" proper for a similar jam to the earlier "Wysteria." Not super long but is guaranteed to lift your spirits.

jamchart_notes: Second "Drive" of the year and second to pass 30 minutes. Hangs out in fast-paced two-guitar funk zones until the 15th minute, when Rick leads into a more atmospheric zone atop a bed of Peter's synth. Trevor gets LOW as the band finds an ascending riff akin to "Time to Flee" and works it for a while. Eventually finds its way into a piano-forward zone that seems to hint at "Factory Fiction" for a while. Lands smoothly in a set-closing "Give it Time."

jamchart_notes: Several mins of dissonance kicks off before Rick pulls the band into a funkier mode. Modulates to major and soars for a few mins - but the real work is just beginning. Digging into some evil tones with Peter laying on Vintage Vibe and then OB-6, the band builds into a massive black hole. Cotter pivots into a faster beat insinctively and Rick and Peter circle each other. Trevor blasts his way in just before the 26:00 with MASSIVE bombs before a "River Lullaby" jam develops and closes out this all-timer jam.

jamchart_notes: Hating on this "Rum" is hating on some of Rick's best guitar work of the tour. It's like a spoiled child claiming that the family trip to Disney was a disaster because they had to have cake for dessert instead of ice cream.
Pure hose. There's not necessarily a need for exploration here as the band's excitement pours out into the celebratory music.

The beginning of this is all about the Vibe textures. Peter sticks to chordal work through a big peak before the band transitions into a more propulsive zone, beginning to build momentum thanks to Peter's repeated piano and Cotter's insistence. Rick hangs back to let the drummer lead as Peter throws ideas into the space. Continuously builds in energy and intensity before a hot peak, finally closing out with a few minutes of percussive funk and interplay before abruptly swerving into "A Fifth of Beethoven."

jamchart_notes: Peter keeps the familiar "Hungersite" peak fresh with a repeated descending lick, beefing up his usual comping behind Rick's solo. Barely slows down at all before the disco-delay clav comes in like this version's counterparts from 11/20/23 and Chateau Sessions. Rick throws in some digital sauce as the disco gets more vicious and hits a final peak.

jamchart_notes: 2nd huge "Lee" of the summer begins with reverbed-out clav from Peter. Coasts on synth-drenched piano and Rick's guitar which begins to lead into a darker mood. Cotter rolls on the snare as Trevor burbles up with envelope filtered work. Explores a hypnotic riff for several mins, bringing the jam to a boil before Cotter increases the tempo into a minimalist and percussive zone with Peter on marimba piano. Begins its patient journey home before returning to the conclusion of "Lee." 21 minutes of pure improv.

jamchart_notes: The OB-6 makes the jam feel like it's in a spaceship taking off as the band leans hard into ambient space with a commitment to patience and quieter dynamics. Rick infuses digital sauce under the subtle textures as the jam gets more percussive before Peter transforms the synth into its own pulsating organism. Trevor leads into a new progression as the waves of digital sound continue. Transforms to a beauteous bliss jam not unlike the Raleigh "Pancakes" around the 18th minute and closes with an amazing peak.

jamchart_notes: The Taco Town of “Empresses.” We start with the top slice: an unprecedented six-minute pre-verse intro jam. Then, savor the thick, crunchy layer after Trevor’s bass solo. You think you’ve reached the meat, but then you’re swept into a “River” of “Greens.” Think we’re done? Not quite. The real core of this sandwich is the bottom half, with “Empress” returning for a jam-packed, savory finish that ties it all together.

jamchart_notes: The bottom half of the "Empress" sandwich starts with the same layer that topped the "Green River" center. The band settles into a steady, chill groove, with Rick’s digital sauce poured over Pete’s thick layer of vintage vibes. This section is light but thick, a monolith revealing a slightly spicy aftertaste before dissolving into brief almost "Flowdown"-like dissonance. A final dark spread evocative of Mario’s underworld theme, coats the bottom slice’s closing verses and composed finish.

jamchart_notes: Modulates quickly into an efficient and beautiful hose jam.

Seventeen months younger and still cutting his teeth, Eugene's baby brother enchants the neighboring northwest with a worthy, if less mature, reprise. Built on a bed of vintage vibes and a steady, pulsing bassline, the performance explores a richly textured, atmospheric space as Rick patiently vamps until finding a hook around the 14-minute mark. For the last few minutes, the band shifts to a dancier chordal groove that never fully realizes its potential, dissolving instead into "Turned Clouds."

Another great S1 closer that starts forebodingly with some minor key piano and is driven forward by tribalistic drumming. After a little tension, Rick settles back gently and melodically before band patiently and collectively builds up to EMG’s typical ripping conclusion. Cotter truly shines throughout

Grungy double guitar rock and roll takes a magical tour through blisstown. Gorgeous melodic finish before slipping into "Electric Avenue." Very reminiscent of the SPAC version from earlier in the month.

Machine gun fire drowns out the engines roar as the vehicle veers off the road in a raging inferno. Speed up. Target marked. Repeat. Targets in the rear view spin out in perfectly timed oil slicks. Patterns repeat mechanically as the G-6155 races, explosions mirroring the pits of our drivers eyes. A boat house looms on the horizon as a helicopter blasts impassable craters in the road ahead. Now airborne our driver ignites and spins skyward shrieking as whirling blades & debris plummet toward scorched earth.

Ecstasy. Infectious optimism. Pure Joy. Rick finds a repeating hook at 7:45 that he builds around before an explosion of guitar Rock Goddery. Every time you think he's found the apex of energy within the peak, he unlocks a new level of earworm shredding. He then slows down, brilliantly going back into the earlier riff before deciding to hose down the crowd one last time. This song DELIVERS as a set closer.
Great section later in the jam akin to the Westville "Rockdale," a demented and askew motif thanks to Cotter's urging.
Some heavier riffing in the latter half of the jam makes this version stand out from the 2024 pack.

Equal parts vibesy vibes, angular reverse delay, Big T fulcrum lines, cyclonic tribal toms, digital sauce, and staccato guitar attack, all culminating in a plucked-from-thin-air melody for Rick's closing solo, permuted several times before dissolving into the composed ending. Sultrily stirred.

jamchart_notes: Two-guitar Goose reflects the first light of sunrise, its shamanic texture a tribute to the crisp dawn. The band patiently floats in that space before shifting into a frenetic and exploratory Ted-like jam. Returning to the song structure, Pete transitions to punctuated keys, inviting Rick into a cyclical step-jam typical of “Madhuvans.” With callbacks to the earlier “Mais Que Nada,” Rick builds to a deliberate peak, both provoked and matched by Trevor’s fierce, Cliff Burton-like bassline.

jamchart_notes: Balancing audacity and restraint, this jam showcases Rick’s knack for running wild with freshly unearthed ideas. As the song leaves its post-verse melody, Rick introduces a palm-muted staccato line, tinkering before shifting to double time and weaving it into the opening melody. By 14 minutes, the jam plunges into a darker, synth-laden space, with Cotter steering the refashioned groove into shadowy depths. The melody returns as a blissy yet thunderous psalmic exploration that segues to the composed close.

jamchart_notes: The first half unfolds as quintessential 2024 “Tumble,” delivering its upbeat, major-key, danceable funk. Around 11 minutes, Rick takes the reins, steering into darker, exploratory space. With a probing lead, he unearths a hook, looping and variating it over Cotter’s rolling toms. By 16 minutes, with the sections fully baked, Cotter propels the jam with increased tempo and intricacy. Rick rides the momentum into a sprawling, “So Ready”-styled jam before dropping into “Tumble’s” composed ending.

jamchart_notes: Peter pulls several incredible earworms out of nowhere early on as Rick hangs back on minimalist rhythm. Trevor suggests a progression that will inform the rest of the jam as all five band members listen incredibly closely to each other. The key here is restraint from Rick - and when he finally lets go for the peak, it's nothing short of spectacular. MUST-HEAR.
shownotes: The encore featured the live debut of "Dracul," Rick's new DeLuis guitar.

jamchart_notes: First significant Boat in a LONG time goes AGGRESSIVE funk. Rick alternates between sharp MuTron and distorted leads while Peter sets up a slick arpeggiator. Punchy Vintage Vibe then carries things before spacing out and coasting atop the twinkling space sounds into an equally as dancey "Fish in the Sea."
shownotes: The encore featured the live debut of "Dracul," Rick's new DeLuis guitar.

jamchart_notes: Bingo “FITS” finally meets its match, stepping into the ring like Tyson facing Paul. The lockdown-tested heavyweight takes on Cincy’s arpeggiated, perennially online underdog — brimming with digital flair, youthful creativity, nimble footwork, and fog machine bravado. It’s a decision by points, with this scrappy “Fish” revealing new motifs, layers, sounds and overall vibes for one of the best covers in the catalogue.
shownotes: The encore featured the live debut of "Dracul," Rick's new DeLuis guitar.

jamchart_notes: Early aggressive clav work from Peter glides smoothly through a peak before things shift into a contemplative mode. A repeating riff on marimba piano allows for Trevor to really stick out around Cotter's insistent drumming and Rick's subtle riffing.

A thick, grimy soundscape with heavily distorted vibes, Trevor in beast mode, Rick Marshall stack-like overdriven vamping, and a handful of perfectly-placed Jebb bass bombs. A sonic full-frontal assault. If War on Drugs covered “Arrow,” it would sound like this.

jamchart_notes: Part of an absolutely flawless second set, the most adventurous "Engborg" to date explodes out of "Running Up That Hill" as the band plays with dynamics on the jam. Peter adds some synth before Rick pulls us back into peak mode, blows the roof off the Brady Center, and fades unfinished into "Sinnerman."
Eschews the standard 2024 "Saints" motif in favour of a slow and breathtakingly gorgeous jam. Peter leans hard into the Vintage Vibe as Rick pours an incredible amount of emotion into his solo.

jamchart_notes: At a svelte 15 minutes, one of the year’s most satisfying and efficient performances. Out of the verses, it drops immediately into a patient half-time jam undergirded by sultry organ and Big T funk. Channeling David Gilmour, Rick fills space with the fewest possible notes, crafting an ethereal soundscape. Lead guitar takes to the fore with a bluesy jam that dissolves into a brief Rush-like prog passage before building to a  satisfying tension-and-release peak.

jamchart_notes: A bonded pair of Entities strafe over the abandoned capital city raining molten cataclysmic destruction and salted earth. Time skipping through the ether bubble we emerge underground to witness VOID then the faint glow of long-dead embers reignited in a haunting pulse of malevolent shades of red and sparkling whites. Coalescing to crystalline form the patterns blink in ancient code as structure takes form stretching outward sprouting into a vast shallow sea of shimmering fractalien beauty. Life finds a way.

jamchart_notes: The late-blooming younger brother of 24's monstrous high-school quarterback and homecoming king, "Cap Drive." The sibling resemblance is unmistabkle, with the same prominent good looks and form. But while 24's two-guitar Goose section immediately unleashes a colossal wall of sound, this one ambles through the halls of adolescent uncertainty before finally finding its senior-year stride — ignited by Rick’s delicate yet forceful guitar-work, Pete’s sudden organ attack, and Cotter’s thunderous drumming.

jamchart_notes: The most remarkable thing about this “Animal” is how unexpectedly non-"Animal" it reads. A listener jumping in blindly right after the verses could easily get lost in the sauce of a typical “Arcadia” jam. We find Ricky doing that trademark Ricky thing, with a gradual sustained build patiently transforming a simple musical idea into a high-energy, major-key bliss explosion. This rendition portends of only good things for “Animal," quite possibly as the next big jam vehicle.

jamchart_notes: Most exploratory version to date hangs in some low-key funk out of the gate. Peter hits some squishy synth as Rick takes to wah - but washes of OB-6 quickly spaces things out and the band expands outward into a gorgeous zone where Rick pulls on the "One In, One Out" melody to take us home through a final peak.

Dark and shreddy, Rick really dominates this cool outside-the-box version. Stays in one space for a large portion, and goes, unfinished, into "California Magic" just as it sounds like the band is ready to explore a new idea.

First of two behemoth versions from Winter '25. Two-guitar Goose at its FINEST. Rick and Peter get scratchy as Trevor leads Cotter into a heavy and dark space. From there, it's all-out pandemonium as the band moves from one menacing idea to the next, shifting and evolving through tones as the tension just builds and builds. Explodes into a peaky section as Cotter RELENTLESSLY pushes the pace through the finish.
First show-opening version ever sets the tone for an incredible night with an efficient and well-paced peak jam.

Massive first-set version heads from usual minor-key space into some classic Winter '25 musings, opening way up with dark Rick and Peter. Hits an early peak in a vicious mode before Cotter picks up the pace and things get intensely psychedelic. Reverb clav twines with guitar melodies as the two find a new tension-filled riff and let it simmer and boil before things hit a final wave of tension into the cathartic "EMG" ending. Your jaw will be on the floor.

Celebratory, uplifting, and charging as the band coalesces around a single idea and rips through it in a way that will have you punching the roof of your car in excitement. Phenomenal set-closing peak in an absolutely incredible show that fades out unfinished.

An immediate GOAT contender, this longest-to-date “FITS” sits shoulder to shoulder with Bingo and Taboose versions. The conventional arpeggiated theme and rock-anthem guitar hero riff are swiftly eschewed in favor of a re-sequenced “Stranger Things”-inspired synth line. Pete layers commanding piano and evocative vibes to create a lush sonic bed over which Rick unleashes an expansive solo evoking 90s-era Santana.

First version to break free of its boundaries carries the energy of the surprise jammed-out "FITS" that came right before. Upbeat, rocking, and celebratory, the band never strays too far into the unknown but keeps up some amazing energy throughout before winding its way home. Possibly an indication that there are plans for bigger excursions in the future...

Gets minor, dark, and Westville "Rockdale"-y with all the best notes. Frenetic and uneasy piano gets cloudy among busy work from Rick as Cotter propels the whole thing. Quiets after a spell and seems to be building to a huge major-key explosive finish, but the band stays minor and Peter pours on some distorted clav as they crash through a final peak and fade > to "Dripfield" before you have time to collect your thoughts.

footnote: With Shine On You Crazy Diamond teases from Peter.
jamchart_notes: Low-key funk eventually dissolves into a propulsive-yet-ambient space coloured by Peter's reverb clav. Rick goes into his loops as Peter throws out the "Shine On You Crazy Diamond" intro lick before gutiar returns to the fray with an intensely psychedelic Mu-Tron peak.

jamchart_notes: Pretty standard 20-minute peaky "Tumble" gets bolstered by Winter 2025 dissonance seeping into the tension builds toward the end. Would not be notable in 2024 but it's is a different band on this tour.

Cotter is the star in the punishing first half. Once the first peak has been exhausted, the band seems to be setting up a segue but instead opts for several minutes of gorgeous major-key play before cooling off into "A Western Sun."

One of the best "short" jams Goose has ever played. Nasty, dark, brooding - the whole package. We only can dream of where this would have gone beyond 11 minutes, but the band opts to pull into a truncated "Wysteria" somewhat abruptly.
Feel-good disco show-opening jam. No warm-up needed here.

jamchart_notes: Opening a second set for the first time in nearly two years, "Arc" picks up right where Goosemas and Milwaukee left off with an adventurous jam. While it still retains a sense of the song for its duration, Peter leads the way into intense psychedelia with heavy Moog Muse usage as Rick augments his tone and does the same. Absolutely incredible sustained energy in this one.

Hailing from Canada after its longest gap in several years, this "Hoserwood" delivers "Rosewood's" finest performance since at least the Cap in 2024. Immediately launching into an upbeat, high-energy, hose jam imbued with a bluesy, Allman-esque rock vibe, it eventually downshifts to near silence. From there, a thundering percussive segment builds with a Middle Eastern-accented theme reminiscent of a "Tumble" jam, ultimately ending rather abruptly and unceremoniously.

songname: Christmas Card From A Hooker In Minneapolis

jamchart_notes: Breaking the longest stretch on the bench since its debut, this "Flee" departs standard play quickly thanks to Rick diving into loops. Creating a hypnotic atmosphere in tandem with the repeating sounds, Peter lays down some piano riffs as we stretch out. Cotter lays in some excellent cymbal washes before upping the tempo and energy while Rick takes us through a seriously blistering peak. Fades atop the toms and slides -> into "Atlas Dogs."

Pleasant major-key space evolves quickly with Rick on some very purposeful melodic leads overtop Peter's synth drone. Cools from there as the band finds a darker progression, Rick augments his tone, and we're off to the races. Some serious Rick fireworks as the energy ramps up, matched beautifully by Peter's repetitive piano work. Boils into a wild tension-build before coming home strong.

Calls back to the 12/13/24 "Hungersite" in the way that Peter builds a repetitive soaring riff on clav for the first part. The band hits a beautiful peak before cooling into a minute of moody play akin to Ted Tapes cut "Arrokoth" before moving on to "Interlude II."
Major key post-rock progressions into blistering crescendos? Sign us up for MORE. OF. THIS. PLEASE. Absolutely crushed this hallowed cover, making it their own in yet another whole new way.

jamchart_notes: Even the Benatar cover received a little extra mustard on this night. Peter lays down a bed of synth effects and bouyant vintage vibes for Rick to emote over, delivering a slowly woven lyrical crescendo thematically akin to the Schuyler Sisters theme in Hamilton, notably showcased in "Satisfied".

jamchart_notes: Some of the best amorphous jamming yet. Fans of the Eugene "Borne" will enjoy this next phase in the evolution of the ambience/texture over melody/structure model. Peter's inpsirational synth work melds with full band to evoke the serene feeling of ice floes in the arctic gently undulating in the waves under the aurora borealis, while a pod of whales calls to the heavens. Rick tugs the OIOO theme back in over this 90's new age excursion in a truly stunning fashion, not a dry eye in the house, into "Animal".

jamchart_notes: First version to ever open a second set and it's immediately right at home. Absolute two-guitar RAGEFEST cools off juat after the 16min mark but Cotter refuses to let the momentum fade and continues his all-out assault on the toms. Peter makes the switch to piano as Rick throws wah-delay riffs around and things explode through another phenomenal peak. Instead of a quick segue, the band then opts for a few minutes of gorgeous major-key play that acts as a prelude to a fantastic "This Old Sea."
shownotes: Love Is A Battlefield was played for the first time since June 23, 2024 (55 shows).

jamchart_notes: This first “Sea” of ‘25 jettisons the tender vocal reprise that had come to characterize some of ‘24’s finest voyages. The band steers toward the rolling, tempestuous format of past “Seas,” with Rick sprinkling southern rock-tinged runs over Cotter’s crashing waves. Calmer waters welcome a brief but gorgeous buoyant theme that signals landfall via a patient and perfect segue -> to "Creatures."

jamchart_notes: A "Hot Tea" encore for a Friday rager must be your average dance party...right? This absolutely unhinged version comes complete with Cotter and Trevor solo breaks before diving headlong into Westville "Rockdale" territory for several minutes of sustained dissonance. Just when you think it's time to rip back into the ending, the band finds a new vein of inspiration and continues to pour tension over everything. An all-timer performance.
shownotes: Love Is A Battlefield was played for the first time since June 23, 2024 (55 shows).

jamchart_notes: Repurposing the closing note of "Give It Time" as the first note of a surprise standalone "(dawn)", this unfinished version launches into a freeform jam at the mid-point (similarly to the jammed "SOS" the previous weekend in Milwaukee). Cotter keeps a propulsive gallop running underneath a pensive Allmans-y lead from Rick until a bluesy deconstruction leads into "Echo of a Rose".

This incredibly efficient "Echo" wastes no time moving into the first of several themes explored during a brief but satisfying 12 minutes. Lightning fast and telepathic, the band bobs and weaves under some rare flat-picking from Rick. A rollicking cowbell-infused jam and a spacy meltdown transitioning into "Jive II" round out this quality-over-quantity jam. Don't skip this one!
Another worthy entry into the saga of huge, peaky "Big Modern!" jams. Closes out this first set in style via some extra turns around the heavy ending.
The younger sibling of 11/8/24. Peter summons a sampled ocean wave (no, seriously) and the band builds a linear-yet-exciting jam from nothing to an extended peak that Rick just won't let go.

After an unremarkable first half to this relatively short 14-minute "Pancakes," the bottom half of the stack is downright delicious. Rick does that inimitable Rick thing, taking a simple melody and bending it into a euphoric, blissful segment.  This shines most brightly at the 11:19 and 13:17 marks, where he runs that melody through cascading, waterfalling runs of pure musical liquid.

The band goes HUGE on the encore for the second night in a row. Gets evil from the get-go with POUNDING Trevor and Cotter as Rick and Peter skip their usual spacey antics in favour of angular play. The tempo amps up and we are thrown headlong into Westville "Rockdale"-style space - edge-of-your-seat madness but with Peter on guitar. Trevor dials in synth effects as it gets crazier, the band setting their sights on the ending but getting there by way of several minutes of punishing darkness and wild sounds.
